nowiki> \u2013 [[Captain (cricket)|Captain]]\n* {{dagger}} \u2013 [[Wicket-keeper]]\n* c ''Fielder'' \u2013 Indicates that the batsman was dismissed by a catch by the named [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]]\n* b ''Bowler'' \u2013 Indicates which [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]] gains credit for the dismissal\n\n==Aftermath==\nWriting for the ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', [[Scyld Berry]] and Oliver Brown suggested that it was unlikely that the players were aware that Christian could have been run out, saying that \"most professional cricketers are most unprofessional when it comes to knowledge of the [[Laws of Cricket|laws]].\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/twenty20/7946832/Outcome-of-the-Twenty20-final-could-have-been-different-had-Somerset-known-the-laws.html |url-access=subscription |title=Outcome of the Twenty20 final could have been different had Somerset known the laws |last1=Berry |first1=Scyld |last2=Brown |first2=Oliver |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=15 August 2010 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The report in ''Wisden Cricketers' Almanack'' went a step further, blaming \"Somerset's glaring ignorance of the laws\".<ref name=\"wisden\">{{cite book |editor-first=Scyld |editor-last=Berry |editor-link=Scyld Berry |title=[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack]] 2011 |edition=148 |year=2011 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd |location=Alton, Hampshire |isbn=978-1-4081-3130-5 |last=Chevallier |first=Hugh |chapter=Friends Provident T20, 2010 |pages=625\u2013629}}</ref> Asked about the incident post-match, the Somerset captain Trescothick said that they \"clearly just did not think at the end there\".<ref name=\"critics\"/> In his autobiography, [[Brian Rose (cricketer)|Brian Rose]], who was Somerset's Director of Cricket, admitted that very few of the Somerset staff and players even knew the law.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rosey: My Life in Somerset Cricket |last=Rose |first=Brian |author-link=Brian Rose (cricketer) |year=2019 |publisher=Fairfield Books |location=Bath, Somerset |isbn=978-1-9996558-5-3 |page=181}}</ref>\n\nHampshire were awarded \u00a3200,000 for winning the competition, while Somerset collected \u00a384,000. As man of the match in the final, McKenzie received \u00a32,000.<ref name=\"wisden\"/> In the [[2011 Twenty20 Cup]], Hampshire and Somerset met at the semi-final stage; the scores were level based on Duckworth-Lewis, and Somerset won the resulting [[Super Over]]. They subsequently lost in [[2011 Twenty20 Cup Final|the final]]; making them runners-up in the competition three years in a row. Somerset also finished as runners-up in the [[2010 Clydesdale Bank 40|2010]] and [[2011 Clydesdale Bank 40|2011]] one-day cup competitions. In 2012, Hampshire won both [[2012 Twenty20 Cup|the Twenty20]] and [[2012 Clydesdale Bank 40|the one-day]] cup competitions.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Domestic Twenty20 cricket in England}}\n{{2010 English cricket season}}\n\n[[Category:2010 in English cricket|Twenty20 Cup Final, 2010]]\n[[Category:Twenty20 Cup Finals]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary:link jargon", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Twenty20_Cup_Final"}
