\n| country           = Pakistan\n| testdebutagainst  = India\n|             testcap = 2\n| testdebutdate     = 16 October\n| testdebutyear     = 1952\n| lasttestdate      = 12 December\n| lasttestagainst   = India\n| lasttestyear      = 1952\n| source            = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/39001.html CricInfo\n| date              = 12 July\n| year              = 2019\n}}\n'''Anwar Hussain Khokhar''' (16 July 1920 \u2013 9 October 2002) ('''[[Urdu]]'''''':\u0627\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u06cc\u0646 \u06a9\u06be\u0648\u06a9\u06be\u0631)''' was a member of Pakistan's first [[Test cricket|Test]] team in 1952. \n\nBorn in [[Lahore]], Hussain was an all-rounder. He played [[first-class cricket]] in Indian competitions from 1941 to 1947, and in Pakistan from 1947 to 1955.<ref name=fc>{{cite web |title=First-Class Matches played by Anwar Hussain |url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/0/929/First-Class_Matches.html |website=CricketArchive |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> He faced the first ball bowled in first-class cricket in Pakistan when he opened the batting for [[Sindh cricket team|Sind]] against West Punjab in December 1947.<ref name=WCA>''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 2003, pp. 1613\u201314.</ref>\n\nHis best first-class performances came when he [[captain (cricket)|captained]] Sind against the touring [[West Indian cricket team in India, Pakistan and Ceylon in 1948\u201349|West Indians]] in 1948-49, and he scored 12 and 81 and took 4 for 66 and 1 for 19 in the drawn match.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sind v West Indians 1948-49 |url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/18/18721.html |website=CricketArchive |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> He was selected to play in Pakistan's first representative match a week later against the West Indians, but with little success. He was a member of Pakistan's first touring team later that season, playing in both matches against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Ceylon]] in [[Colombo]]. He also played one of the representative matches when Ceylon toured [[Ceylonese cricket team in Pakistan in 1949\u201350|Pakistan in 1949-50]].<ref name=fc/>\n\nWhen the [[English cricket team in India, Pakistan and Ceylon in 1951\u201352|English team]] toured in 1951-52 he made 48 in Pakistan's second innings, adding a valuable 83 for the sixth wicket with the captain, [[Abdul Hafeez Kardar]], in Pakistan's four-wicket victory that secured the nation's Test status.<ref name=WCA/> He played in four of the five Test matches in Pakistan's inaugural series against [[Pakistani cricket team in India in 1952\u201353|India in 1952-53]] when he was Kardar's vice-captain, but had little personal success.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pakistan to India 1952-53 |url=http://test-cricket-tours.co.uk/page_1681673.html |website=Test Cricket Tours |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref> He played no further Test cricket after that series.\n\nHussain died in Lahore on 9 October 2002 after suffering from liver cancer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Pakistan Test cricketer Anwar Hussain dies |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/122200.html |website=Cricinfo |accessdate=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cricinfo|id=39001}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hussain, Anwar}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Lahore]]\n[[Category:Northern India cricketers]]\n[[Category:North Zone cricketers]]\n[[Category:Karachi cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sindh cricketers]]\n[[Category:Mumbai cricketers]]\n[[Category:Muslims cricketers]]\n{{Pakistan-cricket-bio-1920s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2405:204:8407:c6b7:5053:afd1:c454:e89a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added information)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anwar_Hussain_(cricketer)"}
